Network peering.

Peering is a direct, point-to-point connection between two networks that lets instances in each reach the other by private address, as if they were on the same network. It works same-account or cross-account, same-region or cross-region, over the AWS backbone with no bandwidth cap.

The constraints are sharper than people expect. The address ranges can't overlap; if both networks use the same range, peering simply won't establish. Peering is non-transitive: if A peers with B and B peers with C, A still can't reach C through B; you need a direct A-to-C peering. And after accepting the request, you have to update route tables on both sides to point at the connection, or it exists but carries no traffic.

The right time for peering is a small number of networks, two to four, that need to talk; because the number of connections grows quadratically, a full mesh becomes unmanageable fast, and at that point you switch to a transit gateway.
